    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="724"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d724">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/11–1844</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stettinius</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to President <persName type="to"
                            >Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-25">November 25,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Subject: Passage of Trucks Through the Soviet Union En Route to
                    China.</p>
                <p>Ambassador Harriman told me that he had talked with you on this subject, and that
                    you agreed in accordance with the recommendation <pb facs="0995" n="981"
                        xml:id="pg_981"/> contained in the attached memorandum dated November
                        15,<note n="31" xml:id="d724fn31">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi>
                    </note> that it would be undesirable to send a message to Marshal Stalin at this
                    time.</p>
                <p>I shall, of course, in accordance with your instructions to Mr. Harriman, follow
                    closely the progress being made on the Ledo–Burma Road.<note n="32"
                        xml:id="d724fn32">Ambassador Harriman had informed the Under Secretary of
                        State that he had told the President that General Somervell thought the Ledo
                        Road was the better route for delivery of the trucks, etc. The President
                        said ‘All right but they should push it when the Ledo Road is open’.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>As you requested, I am returning the memoranda of November 15.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Edward</hi> R. <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius,
                            Jr.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
